76561198010155821,Not Recommended,323720,28187913,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,Alvarion,"""What is a friend?""Question repeatedly seen throughout the course of the game was probably supposed to express the main idea behind the game's story. Despite the fact that the game isn't straightforward bad I simply couldn't resist the feeling that""What is the point?""would be a far better line of questioning.Decay: The Mare is a horror point'n'click adventure game. Player embodies the persona of Sam - patient of rehab institution ""Reaching Dreams"" where he wishes to face his drug addiction. Sadly, as soon as very first night within the facility the place twists into the title ""mare"". Sam will have to face this world of nightmare in order to solve the dark mistery of ""Reaching Dreams"".Click'n'click adventure gameIn terms of gameplay Decay: The Mare doesn't exactly shine. Game is a somewhat crude composition of heavily photoshopped still images. Animated elements are kept to a minimum and most of the game player ""leaps"" between pictures making transitions from one place to another not exactly smooth to say the least. Pictures in general are well made and game provides hints whenever player gets stuck. Regretably due to static nature of the game they are quite painful to watch whenever backtracking is necessary and at some points you have to run from one end of the level to another. Besides this ""Decay"" is a rather standard point'n'click game requiring player to look around for items to combine and utilize in order to solve numerous puzzles. Each of three chapters leaves a little freedom of order in which player solves the objectives but all of them have to be finished to continue the story.Horror experience for easily spookedWhen reception of gameplay might be a matter of opinion it's the horror elements that were the biggest letdown for me. It is commendable that Shining Gate Software tried creating more subtle and psychological experience. Especially nowadays when ""collect ""X"" while running through a dim space for a jumpscare"" appears to be a trend among indie horrors. Pictures witnessed in Decay: The Mare were succesful in creating an amtosphere of persisent uneasiness but nothing beyond this. I've spent most of the first episode almost waiting for some jumpscare to spice things up a little and when it finally came I realised that I started getting bored by the time it showed up. Decay fails to time its spook elements properly and atmosphere thins by the time they appear, stripping them of the impact they could make.I could probably recommend the game to the ones who are easily frightened if they want to get used to the horror genre in small steps. Also point'n'click enthusiasts should find the experience enjoyable. Story, perhaps not the most thrilling, is the definitely the strongest side of the game. Regretably game is plain unrefined with elements like rotating items in equipment menu (used once in whole game) or mandatory scripts triggered by having a peek at a ladder. Decay: The Mare could be a quite good game but perhaps lack of creators' experience was the reason it failed to reach its full potential."
