,Recommended,323720,19696867,"Posted: 14 December, 2015",all,Beanie Baby,"I don't know what to think of this game.I honestly enjoyed the atmosphere the game was trying to convey, this creepy silent hill-esque vibe of the rehabilitation center, the uncanny graphics halfway between static and moving, but i don't know if it was intentional or simply a result of it being a point-and-click game.It's been a while since I played a real point-and-click, the last one being Pajama Sam in the early 2000s when they came into cereal boxes, I enjoyed it greatly, but I was around seven years old.I feel like the format took out the scary edge of the game. Sure, the narrative had potential, but I understood immediatly the limitations of the game. It's a point-and-click. Don't expect a fight scene, having to run away, hiding, etcetera.It is all very straightforward. At first I was scared ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ of the ""thing"" following me throughout the centre, but I noticed how it never really ""came"" for me. Thus the limitations of a point-and-click. No ""real"" action.Still, I looked past this and continued with my exploration. The soundtrack was nice and unsettling, some of the characters (one in particular, if you played you know who im talking about) was fun to talk with and the puzzles needed exploration and some thinking, without being overly challenging. The coin-collecting is fun and unlocks some neat extras, I recommend collecting them, the game being pretty short.To sum it up, I liked this game, even though point-and-click really aren't my thing.I would give it a 6 out of 10. A nice, cheap way to spend time."
76561197982184019,Not Recommended,323720,28299782,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,LakLuster,"On a positive note the game has a solid horror atmosphere and some decent puzzles. However, the nonsense story with a random good and bad ending teamed with some weak jumpscares ruin the experiences."
76561198083068272,Recommended,323720,18079116,"Posted: 17 September, 2015",all,TheBeak,"I'm really picky about my point n' click games.  With the right kind of horrific atmosphere, cool settings, characters, etc. I can get into it but other times it gets to be a real chore.  Decay interested me with its set-up, so I decided to pick this sucker up.  It took me about 4 hours to complete and it might appeal to you if you like the darker side of point n' click like Scratches, Lost Crown: A Ghost Hunting Adventure, Sherlock Holmes: The Awakening, etc.  It's probably better than the first two on my list, but not up to the third.Anyway, you're Sam...a drug addict, a man on the edge, trying to get your life straight in this crazy asylum/rehab facility/group home etc.  From the very beginning it's clear things are not as they seem and the game takes you on Sam's journey through 3 chapters as you scavenge for items, solve puzzles to progress and try to figure out just what the heck is going on.Decay is not a great looking game.  Serviceable.  Way better than Scratches which was hard to find anything because of the ugly, filthy rendering and graphics, but it's comparable.  Still, it's not too difficult to find what you need and the puzzles for the most part are pretty easy if you pay attention to your surroundings and all of the clues you pick up.  You'll  always have a couple of items in your inventory and it's pretty easy to figure out what goes where, what needs combined and what unlocks what.  About 2 puzzles stumped me for a bit but trial n' error is your best friend and even the casual point n' click gamer should be able to figure them out.The game succeeds most in atmosphere.  Your environment undergoes several weird changes through the episodes, and  unusual things will happen in places you've already visited.  There's alot of achievements to get and I got most of them quite easily.  If you back-track and keep your eyes open, you'll find most of 'em.  Though the ""asylum"" setting is getting overdone at this point, it's well used here and there is a general sense that you're being followed and watched from the get go.  Like I said in my Dreadout review...Decay is a game that's not straight up scary, but rather weird, atmospheric and in your head.  I'll remember a couple of the weird characters I encountered forever.  Being unable to die ramps your courage level up for this one, so just keep pressing on.Sound design was solid and the piano soundtrack was cool.  There's not alot of spoken dialogue but what is there is well-done enough and conveys the story, and as an old school game I don't mind reading text, so that was never a problem.  The puzzles were just challenging enough to give you some sense of accomplishment by figuring them out but don't expect a tough, daunting endeavor and you'll be okay.Not everything is perfect here.  The interface can clunk around a bit.  It works alright but it's definitely not the most intuitive around and neither is moving around.  Sometimes when entering through a door, you'll be faced different ways than you'd expect to be facing which can lead to some stumbling around and doofusing your way into the wrong room or direction more than once.  A little more character development would have been nice.  You don't get to know Sam reallllllly well enough...enough to vest yourself in his adventure but I didn't find myself particularly worried or concerned about the character.  The same holds true with the protagonists.  Perhaps, a little more voice acting could have fleshed these parts out better and given a little more personality to the people and creatures that inhabit the asylum.  Although the weirder creatures (who I don't want to give away) were wonderfully well done and total WTF creations.  Play the game and you'll see what I mean.Overall, point n' clickers with a taste for the macabre will definitely enjoy this.  I almost lean towards not recommending it because it's far from perfect, yet it's decent enough for a one time play through.  If you have a pretty free day off work you can beat it in one setting.  Decay is not quite a must have but I enjoyed and those with a taste for the macabre that enjoy classic point n' click should give it a try.  At $10...it's a ""Hmmm, purchase,"" I'd say 5 or 6 on a sale would be the right price.  I'll break it down as I always do!Pros:-Good usage of an overdone setting-Great sound design and soundtrack-Creepy atmosphere throughout-The story does just enough right to keep you going-Fun puzzle solving that is just satisfying enough (very logic based)-Some wild, weird characters that you will remember.Cons:-Graphics are mundane at best.-Could have used more voice acting.-Moving/interfaces are serviceable but a little goofy/clunky-Despite the fun of the puzzles and their appreciable logic design, many are far too easy-Could be more challenging in general (but you do want to push on)-Protagonist is ho-hum-Story could use more emotional investment all around.Overall:  6.9/10"
,Recommended,323720,28381170,"Posted: 14 December, 2016",all,The Jigsaw Man,"Although Steam's store page offers a release date of 2015 The Mare's blotchy resolution on larger wide-screens is respective of a turn-of-the-century GOG title. Grahpics Wh0r3s need not applyA relatively short game running me a little over four hours. I never left the game running while taking a break so my completion time is respective of average completion time for a player of average intelligence.Having said that none of the puzzles were too difficult nor too easy and I used the hint system only about three times; twice wastefully as I only needed to retrace memory a few steps to find a solution.Despite most of The Mare's adventure being utterly nonsensical the third installment wraps everything up with logical explanation. The story, ten years ago, would've been deemed quite profound but nowadays is a common one; no less a couple of important philsophical concerns are suggested.The main reason that The Mare gets a thumbs up from me is the game's ambience. I felt the atmosphere and scenes were illustrated by artists with some understanding of psychology and advanced awareness of emotional empathy and it's romance with locations and lighting; all miraculousy delivered well despite the older graphics engine.I paid $1.50 for the The Mare in it's entierty with all three chapters. I feel it's well worth $6The default $15 retail appears to be lieu of casuals with a large pool of gaming funds; simpler gamers who can not wrap their heads around the miriads of other genre's so only spend on Match 3's and Walking Sims."
